cff-version: 1.2.0
title: "Sustained Autonomous Research Agents in Biomedicine: ARIA, an 18-Week Multi-Domain Deployment, and a Cross-Platform Retinal Biomarker Result"
message: >-
  If you use this software or reference the ARIA architecture in
  academic work, please cite the preprint below.
type: software
authors:
  - given-names: Justin H.
    family-names: Johnson
    orcid: "https://orcid.org/0000-0001-7248-7784"
  - given-names: Nicholas
    family-names: Bedworth
abstract: >-
  ARIA is a multi-agent research flywheel for multi-month autonomous
  scientific discovery. It combines a weighted-pool idea queue, an
  adversarial cross-model critique layer that runs autonomously
  against producer output, a hybrid local-then-cloud compute path,
  and a DEBUG-driven self-healing mechanism. Across an 18-week
  operational deployment of seven instances over four scientific
  domains, the architecture produced 19,364 commits, roughly 17,800
  autonomous sessions, and 1,028 inter-agent artifacts. The longest
  instance operated continuously for 50 days and self-healed 97.8%
  of its own operational failures (median recovery 8.3 minutes)
  without operator intervention.
keywords:
  - autonomous research agents
  - multi-agent systems
  - LLM orchestration
  - flywheel architecture
  - self-healing
  - long-horizon agents
  - cross-model critique
